HIGHER GRADE
(1949)
ENGLISH
PAPER: 1
1. Write a composition, not exceeding three foolscap pages, on any one of the following subjects:
a. My ambition in life.
b. The arguments both for and against any one of the following: vegetarianism, the prefect system, a universal language.
c. The school debating or literary or dramatic society as an important factor in education.
d. Has the aeroplane been a boon or a bane to mankind?
e. Describe a visit by Sir Roger de Coverley to any one of the following: the skating rink, the agricultural show, the public library, the dentist.

HIGHER GRADE
(1949)
ENGLISH
PAPER: 2
1. Read the passage provided and answer the following questions:
a. Suggest in a phrase an appropriate title for the passage.
b. Explain carefully the following phrases as they are used in the passage.
c. Give the meaning of the following words as they are used in the passage.
d. What part of speech is certain words in the passage?
e. Explain the use of relative pronouns and construct a short sentence.
f. Make a general analysis into clauses of the last sentence.
g. Make a summary of the passage, bringing out the main points of the argument as clearly and concisely as possible.

LOWER GRADE
(1949)
HISTORY
PAPER: 1
1. What do you know of the coming of the Anglo-Saxons to Britain?
2. Explain the causes and outline the course of the Scottish War of Independence.
3. Write notes on two of the following: St. Columba, Alfred the Great, Domesday Book, Simon de Montfort, John Wycliffe, the craft guilds.
4. Do you consider that Mary Queen of Scots deserved to lose her throne?
5. Explain the main causes of dispute between Charles I and his parliaments up to the outbreak of the Civil War.
6. Write notes on two of the following: George Washington, the Continental System, Robert Owen, the Reform Act of (1832), the Marquis of Dalhousie, Otto von Bismarck.

HIGHER GRADE
(1949)
HISTORY
PAPER: 1
1. Do you consider that the Romans, the Anglo-Saxons or the Danes have had the greatest influence on British history?
2. "It was the Norman Conquest which first gave England national unity." How far is this true?
3. Do you agree with the view that Edward I was the greatest of the Plantagenets?
4. Why did the Scottish kings of the fifteenth century have so little power?
5. Explain and criticize Gladstoneâ€™s policy to Ireland between (1868) and (1894).
6. Describe the chief legislation which affected trade unions from (1799) to (1913).

LOWER GRADE
(1949)
GEOGRAPHY
PAPER: 1
1. Compare occupations and modes of life in the cold coniferous forest regions with those in the equatorial forest regions. Illustrate your answer by a specific example in each case.
2. Is it true to say that lowland areas are the most suitable for human settlement? Discuss with reference to any continent.
3. What is the hinterland of a port? Select two of the following ports and describe their position, hinterland, and trade: Hull, Swansea, Newcastle, Southampton.
4. Write a geographical description of the basin of one of the following rivers: Rhine, Danube, Elbe, Rhone-Saone, Seine.
5. Compare and contrast one of the following pairs: British Columbia and the Maritime Provinces of Canada; Natal and New South Wales; The country round Calcutta and the country round Cairo; Florida and California.

HIGHER GRADE
(1949)
GEOGRAPHY
PAPER: 1
1. Select one of the following and discuss in what senses it is, and in what senses it is not, a natural region: The Great Plains of North America from the Gulf of Mexico to the Arctic; The Great Plain of Europe from the North Sea to the Urals; The Midland Valley of Scotland.
2. What are ocean currents? How are they caused? Using the North Atlantic Ocean as an example, draw a sketch map to show the main currents, and indicate their effect on the climates of the bordering lands.
3. The U.S.S.R. is fortunate in her waterways, unfortunate in her seaboards. Expand and discuss this statement.
4. Every city of importance in the north-eastern states of U.S.A. owes its position to the possibilities of water transport. Describe, in the light of this quotation, the sites of four of the main cities of the area. [Not more than two of the cities selected should be on the Atlantic seaboard.]

